```markdown {{Citation needed|date=March 2011}} '''Senjitsuhō''' (撰日法, also referred to as '''{{ill|Selection method|ja|選日|1=Senjitsu|12=draft|12=draft}}''') is the method of determining auspicious or inauspicious days in {{ill|calendar annotations|ja|暦注|12=draft|12=draft}}. There are three primary types of Senjitsuhō: '''Tsukigiri''' (月切り), '''Sekigiri''' (節切り), and '''Fudan''' (不断).
== Tsukigiri (月切り) == Tsukigiri determines calendar annotations based on the {{ill|lunar month|ja|旧暦|1=Japanese Lunisolar Calendar|11=Japanese Lunisolar Calendar|12=draft|12=draft}}. Specifically, it uses the days and {{ill|sexagenary cycle|ja|干支|12=draft|12=draft}} starting from the first day (Saku) of the lunar month. A representative example of Tsukigiri-based annotations is the {{ill|Rokuyō|ja|六曜|12=draft|12=draft}}, which includes Senkachi (先勝), Tomobiki (友引), Senmake (先負), Butsumetsu (仏滅), Taian (大安), and Shakkō (赤口).
== Sekigiri (節切り) == Sekigiri determines calendar annotations based on the {{ill|solar terms|ja|二十四節気|12=draft|12=draft}}, specifically using the days and sexagenary cycle starting from each {{ill|solar term's start|ja|節気|12=draft|12=draft}}. Many calendar annotations follow Sekigiri. For example, under Sekigiri, the first month of the year (正月) begins with {{ill|Risshun|ja|立春|12=draft|12=draft}} and ends the day before {{ill|Keichitsu|ja|啓蟄|12=draft|12=draft}}.
The classification of {{ill|kigo (seasonal words)|ja|季語|12=draft|12=draft}} in {{ill|haiku|ja|俳句|12=draft|12=draft}} also follows Sekigiri.
== Fudan (不断) == Fudan is a method where calendar annotations remain constant, regardless of whether they are based on the lunar month or solar terms. For example, {{ill|Ten'enbi|ja|天恩日|12=draft|12=draft}} is always fixed to a specific day of the sexagenary cycle.
```
