{{Citation needed|date=March 2011}}
'''Senjitsuhō''' (撰日法, also referred to as '''{{ill|Selection method|ja|選日|1=Senjitsu|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Selection method|13=User:Immanuelle/Senjitsu|qq=}}''') is the method of determining auspicious or inauspicious days in {{ill|calendar annotations|ja|暦注|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/calendar annotations|qq=|1=rekichū|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11514953}}. There are three primary types of Senjitsuhō: '''Tsukigiri''' (月切り), '''Sekigiri''' (節切り), and '''Fudan''' (不断).

== Tsukigiri (月切り) ==
Tsukigiri determines calendar annotations based on the {{ill|lunar month|ja|旧暦|1=Japanese Lunisolar Calendar|1=Japanese Lunisolar Calendar|11=Japanese Lunisolar Calendar|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/lunar month|13=User:Immanuelle/Japanese Lunisolar Calendar|qq=}}. Specifically, it uses the days and [[:en:Sexagenary cycle|sexagenary cycle]] starting from the first day (Saku) of the lunar month. A representative example of Tsukigiri-based annotations is the {{ill|Rokuyō|ja|六曜|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Rokuyō|qq=}}, which includes Senkachi (先勝), Tomobiki (友引), Senmake (先負), Butsumetsu (仏滅), Taian (大安), and Shakkō (赤口).

== Sekigiri (節切り) ==
Sekigiri determines calendar annotations based on the [[:en:Solar term|solar terms]], specifically using the days and sexagenary cycle starting from each {{ill|solar term's start|ja|節気|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/solar term's start|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 二十四節気|1=solar term|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q1190993}}. Many calendar annotations follow Sekigiri. For example, under Sekigiri, the first month of the year (正月) begins with [[:en:Lichun|Risshun]] and ends the day before [[:en:Jingzhe|Keichitsu]].

The classification of [[:en:Kigo|kigo (seasonal words)]] in [[:en:Haiku|haiku]] also follows Sekigiri.

== Fudan (不断) ==
Fudan is a method where calendar annotations remain constant, regardless of whether they are based on the lunar month or solar terms. For example, {{ill|Ten'enbi|ja|天恩日|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ten'enbi|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 暦注下段|1=rekichuugedan|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11514957}} is always fixed to a specific day of the sexagenary cycle.

